C++ has built-in containers that help store and organize data. One
of these is the map, which stores key-value pairs. This means each
piece of data is linked to a unique key, kind of like how names are
linked to phone numbers in your contacts.
• For this activity, explain how a map works and give a real-life
example of something that functions like a map. It could be a
dictionary (word and definition), a student roster (ID and name), or
a username and password list.
• Focus on helping someone who has never coded before understand
why this kind of container is useful.


In C++, maps are used to store and retreive information in an organzied fashion. 
Using key-value pairs, map items are accessed using keys, which each correspond to 
their associated value in the map. Python has a similar concept, with dictionaries, 
that allows you to retreive values using keys, but for an unfamiliar programmer, 
maps can function like a vending machine. A key value D3 for example, could 
correspond to doritos, while key value A2 could correspond to a snickers bar. All 
Item codes and items are in the same vending machine, but they each correspond to 
their own vending machine item. Using the key value (the vending machine code such 
as A1, A2, A3, B1, B2, B3, C1...) you can access the snack item. A map is just a 
digital version of this using c++ code that stores objects in a virtual space. It 
can be used for storing all sort of information, like names and an associated value
 such as bank information. 
